The Randall-Bold WTP operating procedures are maintained in a current and accurate status through implementation of MOC, periodic review, and suggested revisions.  The level of MOC review performed depends on the complexity of the change. The MOC procedure, found in Section 12 of the CCWD Process Safety Management Manual, includes criteria based to determine the appropriate level of employee review and participation.

Periodic review of operating procedures is also performed.  During this review, the Senior Operator reviews and revises operating procedures as necessary, or as requested by Plant Operators.  All revisions are forwarded to Plant Operators for review and comment.  Upon completion of Plant Operators review, the Senior Operator makes changes as necessary.  The revised procedures are then forwarded to the Plant Supervisor for review and approval.  If necessary, the Plant Supervisor makes revisions and forwards the revised procedures to the Senior Operator to reinitiate the review cycle.  After all parties have reviewed and approved of the revised procedures, the procedures are certified by the Supervisor and placed into affect through training as described below.

Training

CCWD believes that employees who clearly understand how to safely operate a process can play a key role in significantly decreasing the number and severity of incidents, and increasing operating efficiency. A thorough training program focused on facility specific operating procedures and safe work practices is one of the key elements of an effective prevention program.

